Sorry about the earlier comment, I think Anoop may have explained this to me in the past.

The policy is a bit more complicated.  The checksum files should be on dist, so that the main files on the mirrors can be verified.  But only the most recent release should be on the mirrors. The older releases should be on the archive site.
I can't see where the tests failed.

We can suffice with using the following for the download location:
https://www.apache.org/dyn/closer.lua/trafodion

This makes it future proof as it does not point to a specific release. The selected mirror will show the correct version..

+1 Looks good to me. This could have caused memory corruption in some part of the code.

Just to explain the fix: Formerly, when using SECOND(0), the code would cast the DAY(n) TO SECOND(0) to a SECOND(m) datatype. However, INTERVAL SECOND(m) is actually INTERVAL SECOND(m,6) (that is, the fractional part defaults to 6). But in these examples, there is no fractional part. So, the code has been changed so the cast is to SECOND(m,0) instead.
